In[142]:
import pandas as pd

# Renaming columns for clarity
co2_df.rename(columns={'ds': 'date', 'co2': 'CO2'}, inplace=True)
temp_df.rename(columns={'ds': 'date', 'temp': 'Temperature'}, inplace=True)

# Converting dates to datetime format
co2_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(co2_df['date'])
temp_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(temp_df['date'])

# Rounding CO2 dates to the start of the month
co2_df['date'] = co2_df['date'].dt.to_period('M').dt.to_timestamp()

# Checking for missing dates
complete_date_range = pd.date_range(start='1958-03-01', end='2019-05-01', freq='MS')
missing_dates_co2 = complete_date_range.difference(co2_df['date'])
missing_dates_temp = complete_date_range.difference(temp_df['date'])

print(f"Missing dates in CO2 data: {missing_dates_co2}")
print(f"Missing dates in Temperature data: {missing_dates_temp}")

# Filling missing dates in CO2 data
co2_full_df = pd.DataFrame({'date': complete_date_range}).merge(co2_df, on='date', how='left')
co2_full_df['CO2'] = co2_full_df['CO2'].fillna(method='ffill')

# Merging the datasets on the 'date' column
merged_df = pd.merge(co2_full_df, temp_df, on='date', how='inner')

# Displaying the first few rows of the merged dataset and check the number of rows
print(merged_df.head())
print(f"Number of rows in the merged dataset: {len(merged_df)}")

# Basic statistics
print(merged_df.describe())

# Time series plots
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# CO2 plot
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
plt.plot(pd.to_datetime(merged_df['date']), merged_df['CO2'])
plt.title('CO2 Levels Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('CO2')

# Temperature plot
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
plt.plot(pd.to_datetime(merged_df['date']), merged_df['Temperature'])
plt.title('Temperature Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Temperature')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Verbal Summary of the EDA:

  1. The CO2 dataset contains CO2 levels measured over time.The Temperature dataset contains temperature measurements over time.
  2. After merging and filling missing dates, the dataset contains 735 rows of data, indicating a full set of monthly records.
  3. Basic statistics show the mean, standard deviation, and quartiles for both CO2 and temperature data.
  4. Time series plots indicate the trends and seasonal patterns in the data.
  5. We observe that CO2 levels generally increase over time, while temperature also shows noticeable seasonal variation.

merged_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(merged_df['date'])
merged_df.set_index('date', inplace=True)

# Splitting the data
train_size = int(len(merged_df) * 0.8)
train, test = merged_df[:train_size], merged_df[train_size:]

# Displaying the split sizes
print(f"Training set size: {len(train)}")
print(f"Test set size: {len(test)}")

# Plotting the data

plt.ylabel('Temperature')
plt.legend()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import acorr_ljungbox
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import pmdarima as pm
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error

# Fitting ARIMA model using auto_arima
arima_model = pm.auto_arima(train['Temperature'], seasonal=False, trace=True, error_action='ignore', suppress_warnings=True)

# Printing model summary
print(arima_model.summary())

# Using the ARIMA model for prediction
arima_predictions = arima_model.predict(n_periods=len(test))
test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA'] = arima_predictions

# Calculating naive forecast (last observed value in the training set)
naive_forecast = train['Temperature'].iloc[-1]
test['Naive_Forecast'] = naive_forecast

# Performance metrics
mae_arima = mean_absolute_error(test['Temperature'], test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA'])
mse_arima = mean_squared_error(test['Temperature'], test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA'])
mape_arima = np.mean(np.abs((test['Temperature'] - test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA']) / test['Temperature'])) * 100
smape_arima = 100 / len(test) * np.sum(2 * np.abs(test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA'] - test['Temperature']) / (np.abs(test['Temperature']) + np.abs(test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA'])))

# Printing the performance metrics for ARIMA
print(f'MAE (ARIMA): {mae_arima}')
print(f'MSE (ARIMA): {mse_arima}')
print(f'MAPE (ARIMA): {mape_arima}')
print(f'sMAPE (ARIMA): {smape_arima}')

import pmdarima as pm
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import acorr_ljungbox
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error
import numpy as np

# exogenous variables
exog = merged_df[['CO2']]

# Splitting data into train and test sets
train_size = int(len(merged_df) * 0.8)
train, test = merged_df[:train_size], merged_df[train_size:]
train_exog, test_exog = exog[:train_size], exog[train_size:]

# Fitting ARIMA with external regressor
model = pm.auto_arima(train['Temperature'], exogenous=train_exog, seasonal=False, trace=True, error_action='ignore', suppress_warnings=True)

# Printing model summary
print(model.summary())

# Making predictions with external regressor
arima_predictions_exog = model.predict(n_periods=len(test), exogenous=test_exog)
test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA_Exog'] = arima_predictions_exog

# Calculating residuals
residuals_exog = test['Temperature'] - test['Predicted_Temperature_ARIMA_Exog']

import pandas as pd

from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error

# Splitting data into train and test sets
train_size = int(len(merged_df) * 0.8)
train, test = merged_df[:train_size], merged_df[train_size:]
exog_train = train[['CO2']]
exog_test = test[['CO2']]

# Fitting ARIMA with external regressor using SARIMAX
model_exog = SARIMAX(train['Temperature'], exog=exog_train, order=(1, 1, 1), seasonal_order=(1, 1, 1, 12))
model_exog_fit = model_exog.fit(disp=False)
print(model_exog_fit.summary())

# Predictting the test set with the model with external regressor
test_predictions_exog = model_exog_fit.get_forecast(steps=len(test), exog=exog_test).predicted_mean
test['Predicted_Temperature_Exog'] = test_predictions_exog

# Performance metrics with external regressor
mae_exog = mean_absolute_error(test['Temperature'], test['Predicted_Temperature_Exog'])

# Calculating MASE with external regressor
naive_forecast_errors = test['Temperature'].diff().dropna()
mae_naive = np.mean(np.abs(naive_forecast_errors))
mase_exog = mae_exog / mae_naive

# Printing performance metrics
print(f'MAE with CO2 Regressor: {mae_exog}')

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from prophet import Prophet
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import acorr_ljungbox

# Ensuring train and test sets have necessary columns for Prophet
train['ds'] = train.index
train['y'] = train['Temperature']

test['ds'] = test.index
test['y'] = test['Temperature']

# Fitting Prophet model
model = Prophet(yearly_seasonality=False, weekly_seasonality=False, daily_seasonality=False, changepoint_prior_scale=0.5)
model.fit(train[['ds', 'y']])

# Create a dataframe for future predictions
future_data = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=len(test), freq='M')
future_data['ds'] = future_data['ds'] + pd.offsets.MonthBegin(0)

# Making predictions
forecast_data = model.predict(future_data)

# Extracting the forecast for the training period
train_forecast = forecast_data.set_index('ds').loc[train.index]

# Extracting the forecast for the test period
test_forecast = forecast_data.set_index('ds').loc[test.index]

# Calculating residuals for the training set
train_residuals = train['y'] - train_forecast['yhat']

# Calculating residuals for the test set
test_residuals = test['y'] - test_forecast['yhat']

# Performance metrics for the training set
mae_train = mean_absolute_error(train['y'], train_forecast['yhat'])
mse_train = mean_squared_error(train['y'], train_forecast['yhat'])
mape_train = np.mean(np.abs((train['y'] - train_forecast['yhat']) / train['y'])) * 100
smape_train = 100 / len(train) * np.sum(2 * np.abs(train_forecast['yhat'] - train['y']) / (np.abs(train['y']) + np.abs(train_forecast['yhat'])))

# Calculating MASE for the training set
naive_forecast_errors_train = train['y'].diff().dropna()
mae_naive_train = np.mean(np.abs(naive_forecast_errors_train))
mase_train = mae_train / mae_naive_train

# Performanc metrics for the test set
mae_test = mean_absolute_error(test['y'], test_forecast['yhat'])
mse_test = mean_squared_error(test['y'], test_forecast['yhat'])
mape_test = np.mean(np.abs((test['y'] - test_forecast['yhat']) / test['y'])) * 100
smape_test = 100 / len(test) * np.sum(2 * np.abs(test_forecast['yhat'] - test['y']) / (np.abs(test['y']) + np.abs(test_forecast['yhat'])))

# Calculating MASE for the test set
naive_forecast_errors_test = test['y'].diff().dropna()
mae_naive_test = np.mean(np.abs(naive_forecast_errors_test))
mase_test = mae_test / mae_naive_test

print(f'Training MAE: {mae_train}')
print(f'Training MSE: {mse_train}')
print(f'Training MAPE: {mape_train}')
print(f'Training sMAPE: {smape_train}')
print(f'Training MASE: {mase_train}')

print(f'Test MAE: {mae_test}')
print(f'Test MSE: {mse_test}')
print(f'Test MAPE: {mape_test}')
print(f'Test sMAPE: {smape_test}')
print(f'Test MASE: {mase_test}')

# Plotting the residuals for the training set
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(train.index, train_residuals)
plt.title('Residuals of the Prophet Model on Training Data')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.show()

# Plotting the residuals for the test set
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(test.index, test_residuals)
plt.title('Residuals of the Prophet Model on Test Data')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.show()

# Histogram of residuals for the test set
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.hist(test_residuals, bins=30)
plt.title('Histogram of Residuals on Test Data')
plt.xlabel('Residuals')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

# Plotting ACF of residuals for the test set

plot_acf(test_residuals, lags=40)
plt.title('ACF of Residuals on Test Data')
plt.show()

plot_pacf(test_residuals, lags=40)

# Performing Ljung-Box test on residuals

print(lb_test_results)
